segments.text: Yes, there were.
There were drownouts.
We'd take people into the quadrangle, and we'd get as much water as we could, and we'd dump water and mud on them.
Do you remember what it was like going to your first football games?
I sure do.
Describe that.

When you're a poor boy from the radar like me and you go to a field like Kyle Field and you sit with the entire Corps of Cadets and you cheer on a team that wasn't producing a very good record in 1965, it's still exciting to go to the game and to see that many people.
I mean, there were as many people
in that football stadium, as it were, the entire city of Laredo, and that was sort of an amazing statistic for me.
And your yell practice in those days, was it in the stadium?
No, the yell practice in those days was in the stadium.
And was it already at midnight?
See, earlier they'd had them at...
We used to have them, it was not at midnight, it was like at 11 o'clock at night.
Okay, but it was 11.
But we still called it midnight yell practice, but by the time it was over, it would be close to midnight.
And what would a fish wear to midnight yell practice?
Did you wear a uniform?
Haskell, I don't remember whether we wore uniforms.
Did you all ever do any pranks?
No, we would.
We would wear...
We would wear our uniform pants, make sure our belt buckle was polished, and we'd polish our shoes, and we'd wear a t-shirt to midnight yell practice.
But we, one, I used to hate midnight yell practice because it would completely destroy your shoes.
And it was, to me, it was a form of hazing because the shoes that you wanted to always keep, we'd wear boots to midnight yell practice.
And you had to go to class the next day.
We'd have to go to class.
No, normally we'd go to midnight yell practice on a Friday.

And so on Saturday, if you went to class on Saturday, you had to polish those shoes or boots again because they would get completely destroyed and scuffled up because of the parading that went on before midnight yell practice.
And anything that you learned early about what a fish is supposed to do at the game?
Of course, we learned that all.
during the, what I would say, educational sessions that we'd have every day before every meal or every evening before we went to shower after we had study period.
We'd have the upperclassmen, in essence.
As a beginning freshman, how did you communicate back with your family about what was happening and how you were doing?
Through letters, which are still in
A briefcase that I have in my attic right now.
Oh, all right.
Then let me preach you a plea, a sermon.
If you ever, ever, ever are willing to part with those, send them to the A&M Archives so they'll be there forever.
You ought to make Xerox copies for your children so that... All the letters that I wrote to my parents when I was in Vietnam are
Oh, those too.
Yes, yes.
And about how often did you write to your parents your freshman year?
I'd say about every week to two weeks.
And did you get letters back?
Yes, but not as long as mine were.
If we were to summarize what your first letters said, what do you think that...
I think the summary would be, life is not easy here.
It is not...
It is not always fun.
I love my freshman class.
I love my peers.
They're my brothers.
We're all having a hard time, and keep us in your prayers.
They were not mournful.
They were not sorrowful letters, but they were letters that indicated that things were not as...
easy as they as I thought they might have been.
Did you ever think about dropping out?
Oh of course, but I never.
Why didn't you?
Tried and I knew that I could make it.
I knew that I could make it.
When you got when you got your first grades, how were those your freshman year?
At that point we were on a three-point grade point average and I had a
a 2.5, which is pretty good.
So I'd be a 3.5 today.
Right, and I never went below a 2.25 my first two years.

As I advanced in the Corps of Cadets in leadership, I began majoring more in Corps of Cadets than I was majoring in math and minoring in Russian, so my grades started suffering my junior and senior years.
But I never went below a 2 point.

the which would be a three-point today right and when when did you first go home the first the first time I went home was was after Thanksgiving for a couple of days and the second time I went home was Christmas and then there was maybe one of the time I I wouldn't come home but maybe three times no more than four times per year any year that I was at A&M
My parents would come up once a year for Parents' Day.
And do you remember making a court trip that fall?
Yes, I do.
Where?
We went to Fort Worth.
What was it like?
Well, it was wonderful, and the key dilemma for us was we couldn't afford a room, so 15 of us would share one room, and it was not fun.
A hotel room?
A hotel room.
And we, you know, trying to find a place to sleep and
then that was okay.
It's getting ready in the morning and not having enough.
We'd have to get up three hours before we were supposed to get just so we could.
How did you get to Fort Worth?
We caravaned with those freshmen that had cars, and we went together in groups.
As freshmen in the outfit, we'd get four or five cars and we'd go down there.
And did you have a date up there?
Yes, I did.
Where did you get one?
It was always a blind date from Texas Women's University in Denton.
But yeah, I never knew.
Did you write a letter or did somebody arrange it?
It was always arranged.
And a lot of times it was the upperclassmen that would arrange the dates for the freshmen.
And as you think about it now, how were those young ladies treated by the Aggies?
Oh, some were treated...
I mean, Aggies were never rude to the ladies, but sometimes, you know, the worst thing that I would hear was that they weren't the most beautiful.
Because we weren't, you know, you didn't pick them.
Somebody else would pick them.
But they were always, you know, glad to be with an Aggie.
Some Aggies are crude, but most are gentlemen.
Most are gentlemen.
All right.
How did you meet them physically?
Where did you?
We would meet at the hotel room where we were staying, and somehow there would be an arrangement.
So they'd get down from Denton down to Fort Worth.
That's correct.
We wouldn't go pick them up.
And normally did they watch the march?
Yes, they did.
And then go to the game.
That's correct.
Then was there an after-the-game event?
There was normally a dance after the game.
At that time, things were a lot more organized.
You did things in groups.
It was not done like Hector and Sally are going to go here and Frank and Betty are going to go there.
Everything was arranged.
Again, my recollection was that upperclassmen in my outfit and in other outfits would help arrange some of these things.
The, these ladies, you had a dance on Saturday night.
Did you all have a moose pot, beast bucket?
Haskell, you've obviously been talking to other folks, but yes, we would have a moose pot and, you know, the ugliest girl would, you know.
How much money would you put into the pot?
Seventy-five cents to a dollar.
Okay.
No more than that.
But yes, we would definitely try to pick the grossest girl.
And the grossest girl was never really the ugliest girl.
It was usually the fattest girl.
Were you all aware that they had a pot quite often also?
No, I was not aware of that.
As to which guy was the dullest, the dreariest?
Do you remember anything on any court trip you went on, do you remember hearing about anything that really was bad that happened?
No.
All right, of your four years, which were the best for you, which were the most enjoyable Corps trips?
To which place?
The most enjoyable Corps trip I ever made was coming to Austin, Texas, and there's nothing, when I was a senior, and I happened to be the Corps commander, marching
up Congress Avenue towards the Capitol, leading the Corps of Cadets, having my mother and father invited to the reviewing stand and seeing their eyes as her son passed by.
That's something, yeah.
And my mother, Haskell, wanted to look the prettiest she could ever look and she happened to have, she bought a dress and it was orange and I was so embarrassed.
that my mother wore this beautiful orange dress.
My father was in a suit.
I can't believe they were wearing suits and nice dresses to a football game, but people dressed up more back then.

But, you know, having my brothers and sisters there with me and them not understanding what the Corps of Cadets was, but then seeing the entire Corps march up Congress Avenue with the Aggie Band, it was something else.
Oh, that's so special.
Another highlight for me was
It wasn't a court trip, but it was, you know, at a gubernatorial inauguration, but for the Ross Volunteers to be the honor guard for Governor Preston Smith.
Oh, Preston Smith.
And I remember coming to that.
When, on the senior court trip, who else would have been, what other dignitaries would have been on the viewing stand?
Were there some state officials?
People from the Former Students Association, of course, all the, we called it the trigon, all the trigon brass was there.
They'd always have former students who were generals on the reviewing stand.
It was more military-based, and they'd have politicians on it, but at that point, I didn't know the difference between a state representative and a governor.
All right, where did you all form down near the bridge?
It was always, it was, I mean, I remember exactly, it was in front of the Stephen F. Austin Hotel.
Oh, okay.
And it's just been renovated, and it was, that's exactly where the reviewing stand was.
And you marched north to the Capitol?
We would assemble around 1st or 2nd Street, and we would march north.
to the Capitol, take a right on 11th Street.
The band was always at 11th and Congress towards the left in front of the mansion.
I can remember every detail about that.
Do you remember on any court trip the crowd of observers ever being rude or crude to the...
I can't remember that, but I do remember
the crudeness of fans at Rice and crudeness of fans at University of Texas.
During the game?
During the game and after the game when we would lose because we weren't winning many games and the poor Aggies was something that

That's the only time that I saw the corps act in a less than professional manner because the taunting was such that some of the Aggies who were very proud of the fact that we wore the uniform and that we felt like we should be treated better as guests, but the poor Aggie taunting would create the chant of corps fight and corps fight meant
you did anything you could to defend yourself, and you were always outnumbered when a court fight was yelled.
All right, so you go home at Thanksgiving and Christmas your freshman year.
How were you feeling about A&M by then?
Obviously, was proud

have gone there but it was always more comfortable being at home the food was much better the love was greater and the comfort was certainly more accommodating so whenever I went back my stomach would turn and I used to tell my mother and father an hour before I would be picked up please leave me alone in the living room
Because to this day, I hate goodbyes from people I love, especially when I'm going to be far away from them.
And A&M seemed like it was extremely far from Laredo.
In those days, you couldn't drive more than 50 miles an hour, 55 miles an hour.
And so it would take a good six, seven hours to get home.
And I can remember
driving back, I really wouldn't feel terribly bad or have a tummy ache until I got beyond the pass drop.

And then when I could see the Brazos River, I could see the lights of Bryan College Station, and certainly when I could see the lights of the football field, you would begin, your stomach would begin to turn and your heart would begin to thump hard.
because you were always, you always knew that you couldn't be totally prepared for what they had in store for you.
All right, as your freshman year ends, you go for the first time through final review.
On the second march, second part, when you are now, have moved up, how did you feel about being ready to be a sophomore?
It's all been worth it, and it sure took a long time to get here.
Then you go home that summer.
What did you do?
That summer I went home and I worked at Sears to earn some extra money and worked in the supply department at Sears.
And I worked at Sears every summer, my freshman, sophomore, and junior.
What kind of pay?
Do you remember?
I don't remember the hourly.
It was a minimum wage, plus maybe a dollar more above the minimum wage.
And was that extra?
That was a lot of money back then.
Was that extra spending money in addition to what your parents?
Yes, it was extra spending money.
All right, and so you head back at the end of that summer as a sophomore.
Did you begin to feel you were making progress in the Corps and in your academics?
I did.
I did.
I was a, you know, best-drilled freshman, and I began to be very active in some student affairs at the Memorial Student Center, which was... Why?
How did that come about?
I wanted something beyond the core.
I didn't want all of my experience to be core.
Now, that was a little bit controversial because

The Memorial Student Center was known as the place where civilians also hung out, and it was the place where things other than military occurred, and therefore, if you were over there, you might be unduly influenced by subversives, or by liberals, or by people that didn't think the way we did, and I
Again, that course in great books and that exposure to those kind of people said to me, I don't care what people think, you know, I'm going to do what I think I need to do.
So I've always had a little bit of rebel in me, and I didn't realize that I had rebel in me at that point.
I do now, but that was the rebel in me coming out.
Did anybody, as you think back, did anybody encourage you to do MSC?
things?
There were some people that I looked up to that were involved in town hall, especially, because I like students.
I can remember, I can't remember all the names of the folks, but I can remember people that seemed to

be leaders in the Corps, I'm talking about juniors and seniors, seemed to be people that also did things outside the Corps, and where I would see them was at town hall activities, because they had a special ribbon, or they, there was something that they wore, oh, it was the, they had an ascot that was a different color, it was a maroon ascot, and I thought the maroon ascot was neat, and I wanted to wear one one of those days.
When did you meet that fellow named J. Wayne Stark?
Do you remember?
I met J. Wayne Stark my sophomore year, and the person that I got really close to, in addition to Wayne being like a father to me, was Ruth Hewitt, and her
she and her husband were like second parents to me.
So I still remember their address.
It's 1509 Bennett and Ruth still lives in that house.
Now she was on William's staff?
She was the secretary.
That's what I thought.
And so I'd go to their home on weekends just to get away from the Corps and have that special food and that extra comfort I talked about.
And so I became
part of that family, and she adopted me as like one of her sons.
And I began dealing with Wayne as a sophomore.
During your years, did you run into any famous students, students whose parents were rich or potent politicians, or were there celebrity students at any?
I met, Fort Albritton Jr. was one of my classmates, and I knew that he was wealthy, and I knew that his father was active, but I don't know whether he was famous or not, but you know,
Mike Casey was one of my classmates in Hellcat 9, and his father was a congressman.
So there was some fame there.
But how were the children of prominent people, how were they treated at A&M compared to everybody else?
To my knowledge, no different.
I mean, there weren't any, sure, there weren't any special favors, and you didn't know who was rich or who was poor.
Um, nobody knew whether I was from Welth or not, um, until they went, until they came to my home and they saw that, that we had only a two-bedroom house that were five children.
And, you know, maybe they came from a home that had a house, I mean, a bedroom for every child.
And my house, five of us slept in one room.
Were there any giveaway, uh, courses, courses that people took when they knew their... Haskell, no, there...
Were there any special courses for the athletes?
They had special tutoring, but they didn't have any special, they didn't have courses just for them, but they did have tutors that we didn't have.
As far as I know, you're correct.
And as you're feeling, as you're in your sophomore year, you're getting deeper and immersed in all of the activities.
When did you begin to dream about maybe being
high-ranking in the Corps.
When did you begin to dream of that?
I really didn't think that I could achieve that until I was, you know, a junior, and I'd been selected for Corps staff.
Very competitive.
That's the toughest interview I've ever been through.
Now that came during your... That came during my sophomore year.
There were six of us picked to be on core staff.
Do you have any idea what the basis of the selection of those six was?
Yes, I do.
I think one of the primary basis for selection was composure.
Imagine yourself
in a conference room with six to ten upperclassmen, and they're all asking you questions at one time, and you know that there are 30 to 40 people competing, and how I was selected to even
be allowed to go into that room and compete with those 30 or 40.

I don't know how that occurred, but there had to have been some kind of process that the upperclassmen used to say, well, from this outfit or from this wing, we're going to send X amount of people to compete.
Because I certainly didn't have any buddies that were on Corps staff or any ends or any special access.
And you were not an affirmative action...
I don't believe I was.
I might have been, but I don't think.
I mean, I just, I've never felt.
I mean, anything I've ever done, I believe I've gotten done because of some quality that I apparently bring.
I think the main thing that got me through that interview
was my composure and my self-confidence.
And these are students doing the interview?
All students.
As you think back about the questions, were they appropriate questions?
They weren't.
All the questions were either dealing with current events, Corps Cadets matters, or, you know, how quickly you could think on your feet.
They weren't.
These are juniors and seniors.

these were most all these were all the people that were asking me the questions were primarily yeah they were juniors and seniors because they were juniors encore staff and seniors encore staff all right how did you learn that you had been selected after the interview how many were you the only one or was it six there were six of us on core staff how did you six learn that you had been selected
I don't remember the exact details, but I just know that word came down from my company commander, and I found out through my outfit that I'd been selected, and it was... What did your outfit do?
Did they have any special ceremony for you?
There was no special ceremony.
I had, in essence, become a staff rat, and I was leaving the ordinary group.

the ordinary group of people, and I say ordinary, I was leaving my outfit and going to something else, and therefore I was treated as if, yes, I was getting a special privilege, and I think they were proud, but I was also being given a different class status, and there was some resentment.
You were kind of a deserter?

Yes, I was seen not as a deserter, but that I was becoming a staff rat, and staff rats were people that enforced the rules, that made sure that things did not get out of hand, that were seen as the elite of the Corps, and some of the people that used to be

my peers began to see me as a little bit elevated and therefore there was resentment and that's the first time you begin to see, you really begin to see differences in people when you begin to be junior and senior because the rank differences are so varied.
When you're a freshman there are no differences and when you're a sophomore there's only two ranks.
Once you become a

junior the the breadth of rank structure is greater and when you become a senior it's even it's even greater than that so you think this is the spring of your sophomore year which would have been 60 66 spring of 66 and uh spring of 67 67 67
And do you move, you don't physically relocate your dorm room until the fall?
Until the fall.
You're still in, and they didn't do anything to your room or?
No.
Didn't drown you out?
No, no, no, no, no, no.
No, there wasn't any, and you know, I can remember Frank Davis, who was my roommate at that point, was also sent to staff, to wing staff, and so
You know, it turned out that the two of us that were rooming together, I go to Corps Staff, the other one went to Wing Staff.
How did you inform your mom and dad about that?
Did you write them a letter or call them?
I wrote them a letter, or I think I maybe called them on the phone.
Now, you didn't have a steady girlfriend at that time?
At that time, I did not have a steady girlfriend.
I think I got a steady girlfriend my...
So there was nobody else to... No, I got the steady girlfriend.
My junior and senior year, I had a girlfriend by the name of Melita Ruiz, R-U-I-Z.
It was a blonde, blue-eyed girl from Laredo.
All right, so you go home that summer, work again at Sears, then come back in the fall.
Describe the routine for a new staff.
Corps staff.
Corps staff.
You have a cookie.
Let me take a break real quick.
The new routine for a young junior staff officer?
The new routine was a responsibility.
I was supply sergeant.
I had to make sure that every outfit had the proper supplies and that the every outfit needed certain
You know, they had certain needs, like rifles in the Army, and where they cleaned, did they have the oil to clean them?
So my job was supply sergeant, and there were only six of us on Corps staff.
And that's for the whole Corps?
For the entire Corps of Cadets.
So I had responsibilities for the entire Corps, and obviously Corps staff, leads,
the Corps cadets in all marches.
They lead the Corps cadets on Corps trips.
They lead the Corps cadets in all football games.
And so there was some stature associated with being on Corps staff.
Now, the Corps commander my junior year was an Air Force officer, or an Air Force, Lonnie Minz was his name, M-I-N-Z-E. And during those days, the Corps commanders
position alternated between Air Force and Army.
It was that way always.
And so I knew when I was a junior that there was no way that I could be Corps Commander because I was in the Air Force.
So did I desire the top spot?
Yes.
Did I think it was even possible to achieve?
Probably not.
five foot six.

Most Corps commanders were six foot tall with blonde hair and blue eyes, and they didn't have the last name Gutierrez, so I had some odds stacked against me, but I guess what sort of compelled me my junior year to be the very best that I could be was that

I like to compete and, you know, compete in a way that isn't too, too obvious so that you can have the respect of your peers, which is very important in achieving any kind of success at A&M, is if you don't have the respect of your own peers, you don't get anything done.
So you have to compete, yet not come across to your peers as being too...
